nd American domestic politics. Explaining how the Americans used images to discredit the Nazis and, later, the Communists, she illuminates the instrumental role of visual culture in the struggle to capture German hearts and minds at the advent of the cold war.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aPropaganda, AmericanxGermany. 0aPropaganda, AmericanzGermany. 0aPsychological warfarexGermany. 0aPsychological warfarezGermany. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  apropaganda, germany, german, political science, politics, second world war, 20th century, visual, united states of america, american, government interference, cultural policy, occupation, soviet union, usa, ussr, film, movies, cinema, photography, art, artwork, nazis, naziism, communists, communism, history, historical, psychological warfare, iconoclasm, censorship, influences.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226301716423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226301716/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles